{
  "texts": [
    "These optimizers work via the Alternating Direction Method of Multipliers (ADMM), an algorithm that solves large-scale convex problems by decomposing them into smaller, manageable subproblems [8].",
    "This approach alternates between updating the primal variables x and the dual variables y (Lagrange multipliers).",
    "This alternating scheme allows the algorithm to exploit problem structure and work efficiently with sparse matrices, making the solution process significantly faster.",
    "Mathematical FormulationGiven a target mesh to approximate, we begin with a partially deformed version that serves as our starting point for optimization.",
    "Let the deformed mesh be:M deformed = (V, F, E),where V = {1,..., n} is the set of vertices, F the set of faces, and E ⊆ V × V the set of edges such that two vertices i, j ∈ V are connected if they belong to a common face f ∈ F. Let X ∈ R n×3 be the matrix of vertex coordinates, where each row X i ∈ R 3 represents the 3D position of vertex i."
  ]
}